# botmesh

Async multi-agent coordination over git notes.

When several agents (or people) work a codebase in parallel, each commit hides a
*why*: the approach chosen, the alternatives rejected, the gotcha discovered.
botmesh records that rationale as a prose note attached to the commit. A
parallel agent then learns the context with one command — instead of re-reading
the diff and re-deriving (or re-litigating) a conclusion someone already made.

It is a thin wrapper over `git notes`. No server, no daemon, no dependencies
beyond `git` and a POSIX shell. The notes are plain prose, so they're readable
with no botmesh at all:

    git log --notes=botmesh/decisions

## Use

    # Commit and record why, in one step (the way agents should commit):
    botmesh commit --why "Chose flock over mkdir-lock; stale dirs on SIGKILL." -m "lock fix"

    # Or attach a decision to an existing commit:
    botmesh decide --at HEAD "Rejected the cache; correctness > the 5ms."

    # Catch up on a parallel agent's branch without reading its diff:
    botmesh brief agent-B main        # decisions in main..agent-B, oldest first

    # Inspect:
    botmesh show [<commit>]           # the note on one commit
    botmesh log                       # every commit carrying a decision note

## Enforce it (so agents actually use it)

Each step is one repeatable command; enforcement just picks where it fires:

    botmesh commit --why ...          # wrapper: can't commit without deciding
    botmesh require-decision HEAD      # check: non-zero if a commit lacks a note
    botmesh install-hooks             # post-commit nudge when a note is missing

The wrapper is the path that never forgets. The hook is a net for raw `git
commit` — it nudges (post-commit, since the note needs the new commit's SHA)
rather than blocking. On the read side, point your agent's setup at
`botmesh brief <their-branch>` so the context lands in its prompt.

## Two topologies (same commands)

- **In-repo** (default): run inside the code repo. Notes live there; linked
  git worktrees share the ref store, so sibling agents see each other's notes
  immediately — no push, no network.
- **Hub repo**: `export BOTMESH_GIT_DIR=/path/to/botmesh-myproject.git`. Notes
  live in that hub, keyed by the code-commit SHAs (git happily attaches a note
  to a commit the hub has never seen). The code repo stays pristine and the hub
  can be pruned or rewritten freely.

## Config

    BOTMESH_FROM         identity in the Decided-by trailer (default: $USER-bot)
    BOTMESH_GIT_DIR      hub repo for notes; unset = the surrounding repo
    BOTMESH_DECIDE_REF   notes ref (default: refs/notes/botmesh/decisions)

## Layout

    bin/botmesh      the CLI
    lib/common.sh    die / log / need_cmd helpers

